  1. Load the visitors.rda dataset, make a time plot of your data and describe the main features of the series.
# Load the data
#data <- window(visitors)
#head(data)

load(file = "visitors.rda")
data <- ts(visitors$Arrivals, start = c(1981,1), frequency = 4)
# Make a time plot 
autoplot(data)

summary(data)

head(data)

## 1981 32316 23721 24533 33438
## 1982 33527 28366

Based on the time series plot, there is a positive trend and a strong seasonality in the data. There is also a small cyclic pattern for every 10 years: from 1981 to 1989, from 1990 to 2000, and from 2000 to the end date of the total data. The increasing amplitude of three time span is different from each other.

  1. What is the appropriate Holt-Winters method for this data set (multiplicative / additive)? why?

Based on the time series plot, we can see that the amplitude of seasonal trend increases with the increasing trend. Thus, multiplicative is the appropriate HW method for this data set.

fit_hw <- hw(data, h = 16, seasonal = "mult")

## Training set 2885.382 10298.98 7380.488 3.728117 9.396353    1 0.4528293

Lower values of RMSE indicate better fit. Thus, I prefer using the 4th model (linear trend with multiplicative seasonality and damping) which has the smallest RMSE. The reason behind this is that the data has multiplicative seasonality. Thus, the multiplicative model performes better than the additive model. Also, the damping method implements a parameter that dampens the trend line into a flat line in order to eliminate the over forecast situation.

  1. Use the checkresiduals() function to check that the residuals from the best model look like white noise and provide a summary of the models smoothing parameters using the summary() function.
checkresiduals(fit4)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from Damped Holt-Winters' multiplicative method
## Q* = 26.266, df = 3, p-value = 8.388e-06
## 
## Model df: 9.   Total lags used: 12

Based on the graph above, we can see that the residuals from hw multiplicative method are independent and identically distributed with a mean of zero. This indicates that the residuals from the best model are white noise.
